segments.text: So you'd had enough of the military and you didn't want to go back into a military setting.
Yeah, you've got to go into it wholeheartedly again or stay out of it.
So I decided that Texas A&M wasn't for me.
My mission at that time was to get a college degree to satisfy my family.
and then go do what I damn well pleased.
Well, why did you go on eventually then to get a PhD?
During that process, did you get interested in education?
No, I taught a year.
I made exceptionally good grades in Baylor because I always had to make good grades to carry that extra load.
And so I reached the point
along about 19, 22, where I could finish in one summer school at Baylor.
While I was in summer school finishing the, to get the diploma ahead of the game, a teacher, a superintendent from
little town up close to Corsicana.
Came down and was begging a fellow that had taught school under him previously to come back up there and be principal of his high school for another year or two at Lemon Grove.
This guy says, I can't accept the job.
He says, I'm offered a
college job up at Benton in the math department as an instructor.
If I can get my foot on the ladder with a college, I should do that rather than messing around with high schools anymore.
And he says, so he said, well, have you a friend down here that could do the job?
He says, yeah, there he is, walking across the campus.
Well, that happened to be me.
And he says, you can do any damn thing he wants to.
And if you can persuade him to take this job, he says, I'll call him over here.
Well, on that recommendation, he offered me a job up there.
Of course, we had quite a conversation about it.
He paid a good salary for nine months.
I had just turned down a job on a newspaper that offered me $25 a week for the first six weeks.
And if at the end of the six weeks I was still making good, they'd raise my salary to $30 a week.
And by God, from there on I was on my own.
That was the journalistic world.

Well, in competition with $160 a month for nine months, only nine months, at Blooming Grove under this very fine fellow that was really hard up for, what he was trying to do was to get another man or two on the faculty besides himself.
See, man.
I went up there and I finished that job and went back down to Baylor and the old dean that, I can't think of his name at the moment, says, how did you get along teaching school up there?
I said, well, I enjoyed teaching school.
I says, they had me doing every damn thing under the sun.
If they organized, they didn't have enough boys to really organize a football team, but they did scrape together about 15 that got suits up for them, and I says, I wound up coaching the team.
I says, I didn't know how to throw a football.
I says,
everything that happened.
And furthermore, the churches had apparently decided that they had, each one of them, the Baptist church was entitled to half the faculty, and the Methodist church was entitled to the other half.
Well, I didn't fit into either half.
So I wasn't gonna take on any,
Each one of them, yeah, sure, we need somebody to teach this, teach that.
Everything, every extracurricular piece of work that came up, I had to do it.
I told him, I says, I enjoy teaching, but I says, I was reelected.
But he said, if I can get a college job where I,
responsible only for teaching and papers.
I says, I think that'd be pretty good, but if you haven't got anything like that, or if the placement bureau here can't offer me something better than that, then I'm quitting the teaching profession.
And he said, well, you shouldn't do that.
He gave me quite a song and dance.
flattered me about my record for A's and honor points and all that stuff.
And said, you, the teaching, you ought to stay in it.
And so I said, well, you can tell that to the placement bureau here.
Something comes along.
let me know.
This was actually at the, I'd already told them that I wasn't coming back to Blooming Grove, but I was still, I went back to work up there.
And before I finished the job, I got an offer from Gulf Coast Military Academy.
and to teach just about whatever I could teach that they might want you to teach.
So, I took a shot at that and got down there and in a way it was worse than blooming a grove because
There, I became what they called a tactical officer in addition to my other duties.
My other duties were a full-time teaching schedule in the forenoon.
I was off the rest of the afternoon until drill time, and at drill time, I was out there
on the drill field, keeping an eye on my particular company, which was the cadets in Company B.
So here I was back in the military school without knowing it.
They did pay well.
They treated me handsomely.
There was also night duty.
I was billeted at one end of the dormitory
that contained a battery of Company B.
And the commandant of cadets there says, how is it that you're not in uniform?
I said, hell, I'm not supposed to wear a uniform here.
I'm a civilian.
He says, to hell you are.
I says, you're a tactical officer.
I says, I wasn't hired as a tactical officer.
Well, anyway, you're here and you're functioning.
He says, I heard you dress down the company before going on parade, and you was in civilian clothes.
He says, we can't have that.
I says, what are you going to do about it?
He says, well, we're going to commission you a second lieutenant of the reserve.
Oh, I was going to ask you that, how you got in the reserves, and this is how.
I'm going to give you a,
Get your commission, second lieutenant of the reserve corps.
I says, well, I said, I'm not taking any examination or anything.
He says, you don't have to have any.
I'll have my master sergeant picks up the papers.
He'll bring them over.
You sign your name.
He says, pretty soon you'll be a second lieutenant of the reserve corps.
I said, well, there's a hell of a lot of drill that I have forgotten and the drills in the Navy, even in parades, is different from the Army.
I said, if I'm going to be able to service, I'd rather have the Navy end of it.
Well, no, we don't have any Navy courses or naval officers here.
I said, well,
We had a discussion over it, but I wound up accepting the commission and put on the uniform with the rest of them.
Now, did you have to go to meetings?
Go to meetings?
Go to meetings of other second lieutenants?
No.
Did they send you to any kind of a reserve training program?
Hell no.
And was that easy to get into the reserves in the 1920s?
Well, if you've got the endorsement of a...
professor of military science and tactics.
I told him, I says, I don't know a damn thing about, I says, I know the commands for breaking from just what I know from the learned here or have or am learning.
I had learned from reading the manual of arms
infantry drill regulations, I knew how to give the commands to go from a column of squads to a skirmish line.
The command is skirmishers blah blah blah blah.
And I knew, all I knew was what I had learned there as a tactical officer.
During the 1920s and the 1930s, when America was at peace, you remained the whole time in the Army Reserve.
Is that not right?
Well, let's see.
You were still a reserve commissioned officer.
Let me get the book, and I'll give you the exact date.
Okay, let's continue.
I entered the U.S. Navy January 18,
I entered the U.S. Navy as a seaman, January 18, 19.
or January 18, 1918, it would have to be.
U.S. then, 18 January, and I was discharged 18th of July, 1919.
That would be about 20 some odd months, just short of two years.
Then I became a private of field artillery, 7th of January, 1930.
I became a private field artillery, 7th of January, 1930.
And I served in that grade to...
I became a private the 7th of January, and I vacated that status the 20th.
that the 30th of January to the 10th of January 1930.
Now the reason for that is a man to be promoted in the National Guard had to be in the National Guard at the time he was promoted.
So I had graciously accepted the job as captain of the field artillery battery in River Falls, Wisconsin on that second date.
Now you say, well, what kind of, how did you bridge the gap between that?
Well, I went from, I went from, uh,
the Military Academy at Gulfport, Mississippi.
I accepted a job in the New Mexico School of Mines purely for the simple reason that it was a degree-granting institution.
I asked no further questions.
Actually, my remuneration in terms of room and board, laundry and food and everything,
But my remuneration at Gulf Coast Military Academy was more than the $2,000 a year that was offered me as an instructor or assistant professor at New Mexico School of Mines.
But I had told the teacher's agency in Chicago that got the job for me, that not to bother me until there was a job open in a college or a university.
And so this one was the first that they found for me and made a sale on me, sight unseen.
And so I'd accepted it.
Now I got out to New Mexico School of Mines and I was there about three months when they were organizing, reorganizing and expanding the National Guard of New Mexico.

Well the president of the School of Mines was a nice fellow and he was naturally wanted if there were any vacancies or anybody any sugar gonna fall out of this organizing this engineering company at Socorro.
Why he wanted it to be open to any of the boys at the
School of Mines.
In fact, he wanted somebody on the faculty to kind of front and center and get an oar in that deal.
So, I was not an engineer, but
And I hadn't been to any camp or anything as a reserve officer, but I was still tagged with the state and lieutenant's title.
So, well, I saw that none of the other guys were going to front and center and say they'd do it, and I had a disgracefully easy job out there.
My teaching load wasn't...
really, really respectable amount of service for the salary I was getting.
Although it was, seems to be now, actually in those days two thousand dollars as a guy with had no more than an A.B.
degree and one year, two years of teaching experience
$2,000 a year was a hell of a good salary.
What was the teaching load?
Practically nothing.
I had...
I was assistant professor of English and economics.
And everything else needed a slide rule.
although sometimes you use the slide rule in economics.
Everybody else on the faculty went around with these slide rules sticking out of their pocket.
I was the only guy on the faculty that didn't have a slide rule.
My courses were three hours a week for a freshman
a section of freshmen and sophomores.
It was three hours a week of teaching really freshman English.
And bear in mind, some of the students in those colleges

were people, were men 36 years old that had become a mine boss or a mine captain and they knew and knew the game and could run the mine better than the mining school graduate that was superintendent of the mine.
Whereas the superintendent of the mine was

getting at least eight or to nine thousand a year and this guy was getting what you would consider more or less straw boss a wage and those guys are the kind of guys that say well i'm going to the mining school get a degree and qualify for something better so in that in the class that i had of about
of 15 students in each section.
I had three hours a week with two sections.
In other words, six hours at the podium.
And students in front of me, some of them shade younger than I am, most of them,
vastly older than I in both education, mining education and experience.
But my job was to teach them the rudiments of grammar.
That's where I learned that I had to start there.
You can't teach English without the terminology.
So you've got to teach them the terminology of what you're talking about.
And you also at this time became involved with the National Guard in New Mexico.
Yeah.
And you were given, you were made a captain.
Well, no.
No, I didn't get past second lieutenant.
Okay, so you were a second lieutenant.
I'm a second lieutenant and I didn't stay with them long enough to go to the summer training camp.
I went out and
helped to organize the company.
They had two platoons.
One was a platoon of Mexicans where they called the role in Spanish.
The other platoon were students and hired our clerks and whatnot around over town.
They thought it might be a two weeks vacation in the summer.
So I organized the downtown and the students.
I got quite a few students into it.
So there was one platoon that spoke English, the other platoon that spoke Spanish.
Their role was called Spanish
All of the ranks and ratings of the engineer company, of course, went to the white engineering students and men around town that were engineers or knew something about mining.
Well, one of them was a bank clerk, and the other one
of the telephone company.
The captain of the company was the manager of the telephone company.
Then they had a bonafide engineer graduate from the Virginia Military Institute, he was the first lieutenant.
And my qualifications as second lieutenant of engineers was that when the, and by the way the first sergeant was a Mexican.
and a darn bright one and a darn good one.
But my principal duty was that I knew enough Spanish to know when he was calling the roll correctly.
That was the warning I had from the captain.
Your job is to keep your eyes and ears open on this.
So you never went out on maneuvers with him?
Hell no.
I went to
I got a leave of absence to miss the maneuvers, and I've forgotten where the maneuvers were.
I think it was up around the camp at Las Vegas, New Mexico, not to be confused with
not to be confused with Las Vegas, Nebraska, Nevada.
And so you went, you got a leave of absence to go to the University of Colorado to get a master's.
That's right, so I did a master's.
I worked that summer and I kind of knocked a home run with the head of the history department up there.
No, he wasn't headed in.
He headed in a long time afterward.
A fella named Goody Koontz.
Old Goody Koontz was one of my history profs at the graduate level.
And so, Goody Koontz was kind of concentrating on trying to get a grip on what you'd call mining history in the West.
He was a Western.
He was a disciple of the Ternarian theory of frontier history and he was out trying to learn all he could about mining districts.
as a social aspect of the mining frontier, or civilizing influence, or uncivilizing, nobody knew which.
And Goody Coons was trying to nail down a few things on that.
And at the end of, I wrote a pretty good paper for him, I've forgotten what it was,
and I could write fast and didn't mind writing.
I typed pretty well and so I did a pretty good paper for him.
He asked me to stay and he said, you're teaching in the mining school, aren't you?
Had I looked into the nature of the mining districts in New Mexico,
What was the legal and social, legal excuse for them?
Were they governmental units of record?
By what authority did they lynch people, if they lynched any?
And it's a social aspect of the frontier and so forth.
You looked into that?
No, I didn't know anything about it.
He said, well, you've read my study on the subject of the mining districts of Gilpin County, Colorado, haven't you?
I said, well, actually, I should have read the writings of one of my professors, but I missed you.
I hadn't read it.
He said, well, you've been a bit deaf.
and he says, when are you gonna come back to finish your master's degree?
I says, I'm coming back next summer to work on it.
He says, well, I'll tell you.
He says, if you get interested in it when you get back, see what you can do with the mining districts of some area, logical area, of New Mexico.
I said, well I've rattled around down there enough to know where the logical district is.
I said the logical district is a southeast corner, the southeast quarter of the state.
I says there isn't much up toward Colorado because Colorado was already being mined from the north, the big strikes up in
Well, Gilpin County is one of them.
I says, the mining history of New Mexico practically ends with what's being done now and what was done.
I said, he says, well, he says, you're ready to get started already.
He says, you do me a good master's thesis
a good master's thesis.
Doesn't have to be worthy of publication as is, but he says something that you can authenticate.
Says if you can pull something together, he says you can get enough credits on a high quality MA thesis.
that you won't need but one more summer to get the, complete the master's.
But you'll have to come back here and complete the master's, whatever is left, and take the master's final examination, which is a poor imitation of the Ph.D. examination and so forth.
And yes, you have to have one to get the master's from our college, now you have to
have a reading knowledge of one foreign language.
Says, I take it that you know enough Spanish for that.
I says, yeah, I know Spanish as well as I do English when it comes to grammar and reading it.
I can't, I'm not as articulate as I ought to be in oral Spanish, but yeah, I can handle anything that's in writing down there.
So you did this master's thesis then?
in my spare time at the college, of which I was overloaded with.
I had more spare time than I had teaching.
Well, why did you decide to go on for a PhD then?
Well, I did after a fashion go on for a PhD, but not from there.
I didn't want a PhD from Colorado.
It was
I formed a queer idea about PhDs in those days.
If a guy got a PhD highway, if a guy got an AB Missouri PhD,
Missouri, M.A.
Missouri, Ph.D. Missouri.
Well, I just figured the guy didn't really have a Ph.D.
He just dug in enough with one or two departments to get one, and they didn't have any horizon.
Now, I got that theory largely from this fellow Goody Coons.
He told me, he says,
with a master's says, hell that's pretty good for high school work, and gets you a job anywhere in a good high school, and lower jobs than the level of scholarship in universities.
He says if you're going to be a school teacher, you've got to be a university school teacher.
and you've got to get the requirements, meet the requirements.
He says, I'm sure that you can do a thesis on what we're talking about, and it would get by as a PhD thesis in some places.
But he says...
I recommend that you get your PhD from, get all your graduate degrees from a different university.
Why'd you decide on Minnesota?
Well, I transferred there from Chicago for a geographical reason.
I was in Chicago and I had retired
One of my language requirements, I had mastered reading French exceptionally well.
I was already pretty well-oiled in Spanish, and so I boned up reading.
Of course, you don't have to be an expert reader, except in your field.
Now, the vocabulary that you run into in reading one of Mary May's novelettes, or something by, by any of the French authors, real big names, de Maupassant, there's so much vernacular in there that,

You have to be pretty good on reading French to read it in French, but when you get to history, the vernacular that you come into, break into in history, hell you can read, you can read French without knowing a hell of a lot of French.
Because so many of their political terms and their military terms and their
newspaper terms are right there in front of you.
I had no trouble with French.
However, today, if those two requirements were still required in a PhD today, we'd have better PhDs than we're getting.
The modern PhDs
are getting away with murder compared to what they would have had to do back in the 30s and early 40s.
I know that sounds like a braggadocio statement, but I've seen PhD theses today
that I wouldn't give a goddamn thing higher than a C+.
You just go down to the Ph.D. files of some of these colleges that are offering them, and most of the O-line colleges like, well, University of Wisconsin,
they'll admit to you without blushing that they're not requiring the PhDs that they did before the war years or even shortly after the war.
Says the competition, the demand for PhDs to hold university teaching jobs in these universities
created the demand.
Well, unfortunately, the people that are suffering from the demand also have the powers to meet the problem by easing up on the production and then producing more and more.
So that's the reason, if you really want to cry over the deterioration,
of these famous departments for this and that field, says if you want to shed any tears over that, that's where you shed them, is when enrollments jump from 10,000 to 45,000.
It's inevitable that the professors will begin saying who among my
mediocre crop of teaching assistants, and of course teaching assistants has itself watered down the quality of the academicians, academics.
So we had to produce more PhDs to meet our growing needs, and if a man stays on the

in a job as a PhD, as a graduate student in Wisconsin, if he stays there seven years as a teaching assistant, I think the word now is TAs, as a TA in Wisconsin, if he stays there seven years, hell, he has tenure.
under the law.
So the profs down there, I know the problem they were up against.
I saw them in action while I was chief of staff for this, these technicians for these three combined boards.
And they weren't talking about who is best qualified to be
the next PhD to be Captain Gound, but how can we get good teaching assistants and then pick the best of the teaching assistants?
Well, when you begin basing your need upon the teaching skill and subordinating the academic skill, you see, that is a very dangerous switch in the
ultimate objective of what the Ph.D. used to be.
How'd you get an offer to be a college president while you were still in your thirties?
Well, because I was offered a job at the University of Minnesota, to make a long story short.
I thought to hell.
At River Falls,
You offered a job at the University of Minnesota?
Yeah, I was a full professor.
When you got your PhD there?
Yeah.
And instead you decided to become the president of the University of Wisconsin at Superior?
Yeah, which may or may not have been a good decision.
You were a young man at that time, 34 years old or so.
That's right.
As a college president.
Yeah.
I was the youngest in the state and they were shouting about young university and college presidents.
They just brought in this dreamer that was from the law school at Yale.
What was his name?
He was there president of the University of Chicago.
He's been out in Southern California living out there, retired.
I haven't seen or heard much of him lately.
I know there was a very young man that came out of Oxford
that was president of the University of Rochester about that time.
There was a wave on saying we've got to go out and get younger blood.
Well the Rochester guy lasted about two years and vanished, but the guy that came to University of Chicago stayed there a long time.
And you stayed
You stayed there at Superior until 1940.
Yeah.
When you were October of 1940, you were activated.
You were granted a leave of absence for military active duty on October 15, 1940.
That's about right.
And you went into the Army at what rank?
Now, were you captain then?
No, I was colonel.
Oh, they gave you, they made you a colonel.
Well, hell, I had worked hard enough to get it.
Were you a full colonel or a lieutenant colonel?
Oh, I was a full colonel.
Even though you did not participate, this whole time you did not participate, during the 30's then you didn't participate in
Any military drills or summer drills?
To hell I didn't.
Oh, well tell me about that then.
Well, I was promoted from a private in the battery at River Falls.
I was promoted from private to captain for the simple reason
that the captain was a lawyer, and a bright, sharp lawyer named Kenneth White.
Well, Kenneth White
